52x.title: Arbital Math levels
52x.clickbait: How mathy do you like your pages?
52x.text:
Readers come to Arbital pages with different levels of mathematical background. This page gives guidelines for writing pages for some of the most common audiences.

[todo: Write descriptions of each audience.]
[todo: Write guidelines for writing for each audience.]

## Math 0

Main article: **[1r3]**

Readers at the Math 0 level have little to no knowledge of mathematical notation or concepts outside of basic arithmetic and problem solving.

Proficiency at the Math 0 level corresponds roughly to any level of U.S. math education up to the end of primary school, or the sixth grade.

## Math 1

Main article: **[1r5]**

Readers at the Math 1 level have some knowledge of basic algebra and geometry, and solving problems in that context.

Proficiency at the Math 2 level corresponds roughly to the math education level of a U.S. junior high graduate, or the ninth grade.

## Math 2

Main article: **[1r6]**

Readers at the Math 2 level have an extensive knowledge of elementary mathematical concepts, and may also apply them to their professions or other areas of study.

Proficiency at the Math 2 level corresponds roughly to the math education level of a U.S. high school senior (twelfth-grade student) taking advanced courses in mathematics, or a first-year mathematics student at a university.

## Math 3

Main article: **[1r7]**

Readers at the Math 3 level have knowledge of research-level mathematics, and have worked with formal mathematical concepts and proofs. They are familiar with axiomatic derivations of sets and abstract structures.

Proficiency at the Math 3 level corresponds roughly to the math education level of a university student with an undergraduate degree in mathematics or higher.
